VERDICT: PASS — losses and gradients are identical between paths.

Implication: forward + backward through the two injection
paths is mathematically equivalent. The bench-time gap
(memory 0.62 vs hippo 0.27 on grown arms) must come from
something OUTSIDE the loss path:
  1. Per-batch sampling distribution differs (class balance,
     replacement policy, batch composition).
  2. Storage timing differs (memory stores raw x; hippo
     stores L0(x) snapshotted at consolidate). For frozen
     L0 these are identical, so this should NOT matter — but
     verify the storage path doesn't apply any subtle
     transformation (dtype cast, normalization, ReLU mask).
  3. The batch the bench actually feeds at each step.
     Memory.sample(64) draws 64 from a union of 100×n_tasks
     unique reals; HippocampalBuffer.sample(64) draws 64
     class-uniform with replacement from K codes per class.
     At K=50 the per-class diversity matches, but per-batch
     class composition variance differs (with-replacement
     over 30 classes vs without-replacement over the union).
